ariant of   Aleo  ."]}]},{"name":"Llewelyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Llewellyn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewellyn","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Llywelyn</i>, derived from British Celtic <i>Lugubelinos</i>, itself from the divine name <i>Lugus</i> + an uncertain second element often used alone as a name. Through association with <i>llew</i> ‘lion’, it was altered to <i>Llewelyn</i>. This was the name of two princes of north Wales who held the Normans at bay for many years in the 13th century. Etymologically speaking, the form with a fourth <i>-l-</i> is an error, not found as an original Welsh name, but this is now much the most common spelling in the US."]}]},{"name":"Gwilym","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>William</b> , in use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Gwilim","meanings":["equivalent of <b>William</b> , in use since the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Gwillym","meanings":["equivalent of <b>William</b> , in use since the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Gwilym Ap Llewelyn was born about 1279, in Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom as the son of Llywelyn Ap Gruffudd and Jonet verch Dafydd. He had at least 1 son with Gwladys verch Philip. He died in 1355, at the age of 77."},"et":{"Abt 1279–1355":"umbes 1279–1355","1279–1355":"1279–1355","1283–Female":"1283–Surnud","1302–Male":"1302–Surnud","1222–Male":"1222–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1302":"1302","1279":"1279","1355":"1355","1222":"1222","Abt 1279":"umbes 1279","1283":"1283","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom","Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1279–1355":"noin 1279–1355","1279–1355":"1279–1355","1283–Female":"1283–Kuollut","1302–Male":"1302–Kuollut","1222–Male":"1222–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1302":"1302","1279":"1279","1355":"1355","1222":"1222","Abt 1279":"noin 1279","1283":"1283","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1279–1355":"environ 1279–1355","1279–1355":"1279–1355","1283–Female":"1283–Décédée","1302–Male":"1302–Décédé","1222–Male":"1222–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1302":"1302","1279":"1279","1355":"1355","1222":"1222","Abt 1279":"environ 1279","1283":"1283","Wales, United Kingdom":"Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Caio, Carmarthenshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Gwilym Ap Llewelyn est né environ 1279, à Caio, Carmarthenshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni, fils de Llywelyn Ap Gruffudd et Jonet verch Dafydd. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Gwladys verch Philip. Il est décédé en 1355, à l’âge de 77 ans."},"de":{"Abt 1279–1355":"um 1279–1355","1279–1355":"1279–1355","1283–Female":"1283–Verstorben","1302–Male":"1302–Verstorben","1222–Male":"1222–Verstorben","–Female":"Verstorben","1302":"1302","1279":"1279","1355":"1355","1222":"1222","Abt 1279":"um 1279","1283":"1283","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom","Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Gwilym Ap Llewelyn wurde um 1279 in Caio, Carmarthenshi